      {
        "id": 4886419,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2026-03-16T06:57:12.258Z",
        "cooked": "<p>It\u2019s a bit different because it\u2019s two climats that have the same name, rather than being one vineyard shared between two communes. The name means \u201creclaimed field\u201d, meaning a parcel that was cleared of wood/scrub. Of the two I think the Puligny terroir is probably the better, but it\u2019s also uneven as there is an historic part that\u2019s adjacent to and quite similar to Truffi\u00e8re, and then a part that was cleared using heavy machinery in the 1970-80s that\u2019s a lot of broken stone and not so interesting.</p>",
